				<table cellspacing="4" align="center" width="150">
			
				<tr>
					<td><img src="./styles/subsilver2/imageset/en/icon_user_offline.gif" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /></td>
				</tr>
			
				</table>

				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Wed Feb 09, 2005 9:31 am<br /><b>Posts:</b> 418
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I was under the impression that SD is easier to interface with than CF.  SD can provide a more direct interface, while CF uses the IDE interface.  CF has up to 4GB capacities, but up to 2GB in size, both SD and CF are equally priced.  SD has the size advantage, and I am pretty sure it uses less power than CF.  A flash kit based around PSRAM and SD flash cards seems like the ideal route for classic consoles, in my opinion.
<br />
<br />Builtin flash requires some means of programming the chips.  Parallel port is not very user friendly these days, and USB ports add a layer of complexity that negates any simplicity gained by being able to access flash chips in real time.  Then there is the cost and capacity limitations, all taken together it makes SD flash cards plus PSRAM seem like the best choice.
<br />
<br />One might also say that write limitations also make removable flash cards more appealing because once the write limit is reached, you can easily get a new SD flash card... but I am not sure if people actually regularly reach the write limit of their flash devices.  Have people with GBC, GBA, or other flash based backup devices ever reached the write limit of their flash chips?  I could see it happening for developers, but for casual game playing, I just don't see it happening.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
